Components of the Layered Grammar

  • data and aesthetic mappings
  • geometric objects
  • scales
  • statistics and transformations
  • a coordinate system
  • facet specification
  • themes

Coordinate system

  • combines aesthetics to produce a 2d position on the plot x and y coord_cartesian(): the default system

coord_flip(): flips the cartesian coordinate system

coord_fixed(): fixed aspect ratio

coord_map()/coord_quickmap()/coord_sf(): Map projections

coord_polar(): Polar coordinates

ggplot(data=wildfire_table, aes(x=FIRE_TYPE))+
  scale_fill_brewer(type="qual",palette = "Dark2")+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=FIRE_CAUSE))+
  labs(x="Fire Type", y="Total Entries",fill="Fire Cause",title = "Fires Across British Columbia")+
  coord_flip()+
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Facet

Facets allow you to plot many of the same plots by a specific variable.

There are two types of facets in ggplot2. facet_grid and facet_wrap

Facet grid: Forms a matrix of panels defined by faceting variables

mt <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(mpg, wt, colour = factor(cyl))) +
  geom_point()

mt + facet_grid(vars(cyl))

Facet wrap where vars is the column to facet on. Best for one variable many levels. Specify the number of column and rows.

p <- ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + geom_point()


p + facet_wrap(vars(class))

Themes

Theme Components : to modify individual theme components you alter the element. There are four types of elements:

  • text denoted by element_text()
  • lines denoted by element_line()
  • rectangles denoted by element_rectangle()
  • blank element_blank()

Theme elements are separated with commas, not +

plot <- ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + geom_point()

plot +
  theme(
    axis.line = element_line(arrow = arrow()),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    plot.margin = margin(2, 2, 2, 2, "cm"),
    plot.background = element_rect(
      fill = "grey90",
      colour = "black"
    )
      
  )

Parameters in Markdown

Parameters are useful when you want to render the same report with distinct values for various key inputs, for example:

  • Running a report specific to a department or geographic region.
  • Running a report that covers a specific period in time
  • Running multiple versions of a report for distinct sets of core assumptions.

Setting Parameters in the YAML header allows you to assign those parameters within markdown. For example, in the code below we have included file_path as a parameter in the YAML header:

---
title: "Markdown_Report"
author: "Lauren"
date: "April 4, 2020"

output: word_document
params:
  file_path: "./Output/wildfire_2016.csv"
 
---

We can also assign these values through this line of code:

render("Markdown_Report.Rmd", params = list(file_path = "./Output/wildfire_2016.csv"))

To use parameters in your code you can reference them as params$file_path with the $ separating your defined parameter

Parameters

Since we output two different years, lets also set up a year parameter

---
title: "Markdown_Report"
author: "Lauren"
date: "April 4, 2020"
output: 
  html_document:
  params:
    file_path: "./Output/wildfire_2016.csv"
    year: 2016

---

Parameters

Run the same report for the year 2017

rmarkdown::render("Markdown_report.rmd",params=list(file_path="./Output/wildfire_2017.csv", year=2017))

To name output files - create a function

render_report = function(file_path, year) {
  rmarkdown::render(
    "Markdown_Report.Rmd", params = list(
      file_path= file_path,
      year = year
    ),
    output_file = paste0("Report-", year, ".docx")
  )
}

Additionally we can use rmarkdown::render("Markdown_Report.Rmd", params = "ask") for a graphical interface to pop up so the user can input the parameters.
